  <datafield tag="545" ind1="0" ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Native of Scotland; studied at the University of Edinburgh and University of Paris before accepting a position at the Institute of English Studies in Athens, Greece in 1939. Worked for the British Council in the Middle East during the Second World War, then completed his formal education at the University of London in 1952. After a decade at the University of Edinburgh, Catford joined the faculty of the University of Michigan in 1964. He headed the English Language Institute and Laboratory of Communicative Sciences and was twice Chair of the Department of Linguistics. Widely known for his work on phonetics and language instruction, Carford retired in 1986 and died in 2009.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="520" ind1="2" ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Papers contain video recordings and handouts from a series of eight lectures given by Catford before his retirement. Topics include Catford's life and career, various theories of linguistics, and his role in linguistics instruction in the U.S. and the U.K. Other materials include research articles and a nomination for distinguished faculty award.</subfield>
  </datafield>
